.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Proactor \- Completion\-based event loop engine for Linux::Event
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use v5.36;
\&  use Linux::Event::Loop;
\&
\&  my $loop = Linux::Event::Loop\->new(
\&    model   => \*(Aqproactor\*(Aq,
\&    backend => \*(Aquring\*(Aq,
\&  );
\&
\&  my $op = $loop\->recv(
\&    fh          => $fh,
\&    len         => 4096,
\&    flags       => 0,
\&    data        => { request_id => 1 },
\&    on_complete => sub ($op, $result, $ctx) {
\&      return if $op\->is_cancelled;
\&
\&      if ($op\->failed) {
\&        warn $op\->error\->message;
\&        return;
\&      }
\&
\&      my $bytes = $result\->{bytes};
\&      my $buf   = $result\->{data};
\&      my $eof   = $result\->{eof};
\&    },
\&  );
\&
\&  while ($loop\->live_op_count) {
\&    $loop\->run_once;
\&  }
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Proactor\*(C'\fR is the completion\-based engine in this distribution.
It submits operations to a backend such as io_uring, tracks them with
Linux::Event::Operation, and delivers completion callbacks asynchronously
through the callback queue.
.PP
Callbacks never run inline. Operations settle exactly once. Cancellation is
race\-safe and still delivers through the same deferred callback path.
